post_text:
Stilwell Grade School would like to congratulate Mrs. Cox-Wilson on her retirement and thank her for twenty two years of service at SGS.

In appreciation for her dedication to education and Stilwell Grade School, we want to say thank you for believing in our children, for guiding through example, and for inspiring with passion and love. You will be greatly missed as a beloved teacher, coworker, and friend. Our thoughts and prayers will always be with you and you will forever be in our hearts.

If you have a special memory of Mrs. Cox-Wilson, whether she taught you or your child or if you have worked with her at SGS, please share it with us in the comments.
text:
Stilwell Grade School would like to congratulate Mrs. Cox-Wilson on her retirement and thank her for twenty two years of service at SGS.

In appreciation for her dedication to education and Stilwell Grade School, we want to say thank you for believing in our children, for guiding through example, and for inspiring with passion and love. You will be greatly missed as a beloved teacher, coworker, and friend. Our thoughts and prayers will always be with you and you will forever be in our hearts.

If you have a special memory of Mrs. Cox-Wilson, whether she taught you or your child or if you have worked with her at SGS, please share it with us in the comments.

Picture scenes are an engaging tool used to work on articulation,grammar, WH questions, following directions, vocabulary and inferences!

Tips:
-Ask your child questions about the pictures. (Who, what, when, where and why)
-Name and identify objects in the picture.
-Work in Negation (what doesn‚Äôt belong)
- Follow simple directions ( ‚Äúpoint to the chair‚Äù or ‚ÄúPoint to the girl with brown hair then find the boy sleeping‚Äù)

Calling all little artists!

We sure have missed getting to see all your beautiful artwork in the hallways and classrooms!

So, over the next couple of weeks we would like you to spend time on a piece of artwork to send in for a virtual art show!

Whether it be pencil, marker, crayons, paint, digital, sculpture, etc., we want to see your art!

So create your masterpiece, then take a photo of it and email it to Mrs. Mandy at mrichardson@stilwellk12.org.

Please include your first and last name, what grade you‚Äôre in, and a title for your artwork.

This contest is open to 3 year olds all the way up to 4th grade.

The deadline to have your art in is Thursday, April 30th.

Please take your time and put lots of effort into your artwork! We can‚Äôt wait to see what you come up with!

Happy Wednesday everyone!

Here is Ms. Hummingbird‚Äôs lesson for today:

Reading comprehensions involves thinking about the words that were just read and then form a meaning form the text as a whole! Reading comprehension is the ability to read, understand, process and recall what was just read.
Let your child read to you OR read to your younger ones.

Targets: vocabulary, descriptions, reading comprehension and sentence recall.

post_text:
Here is today‚Äôs lesson from Ms. Hummingbird:

Spring Conversation Cards: Why is asking and answering questions important?

We ask questions in order to learn more about a topic and we answer questions to provide information. To answer questions, students think about the meaning of the question, form an answer and speak the answer they formed. To ask a question your child has to think about what they want to ask, form a question in their mind and then produce the question they want to ask.
Asking and answering is part of how we learn! It is important to form complete sentences that have meaning.

This activity targets: articulation, WH question (who, what, when, where and why), vocabulary and formation of sentences.

-Ms. Hummingbird

Stilwell High School will join other HS nationwide on Friday to honor the 2020 Senior Class!

High schools around Oklahoma and across the country are banding together to honor the 2020 senior class amidst the coronavirus pandemic.

On Friday, April 10, at 8:20 p.m., James Bradley Memorial Field and outdoor stadiums around the state and country will turn on their lights for 20 minutes to show their appreciation for the senior class as part of the ‚ÄúBe the Light‚Äù campaign.

The lights are a beacon to show the Senior Class we are thinking of them and to remind them there will be a time where we will be all together once again.

The ‚ÄúBe the Light‚Äù campaign has been spreading across the nation as schools look for a way to celebrate their graduating seniors who are having their final memories in high school stripped away due to the Covid-19 virus.

Take a drive by the field during that time and honk to show your support. Please remember to adhere to social distancing protocol and stay in your vehicle.

Why the exact time?
20:20 for 20 minutes for the Class of 2020!

post_text:
Watch and listen as Mrs. Hammons tells us why vitamin C is super important and also how to make a delicious smoothie!

Why is Vitamin C important? Vitamin C is a water-soluble vitamin well known for its role in supporting a healthy immune system. Because your body cannot make vitamin C, it must come from the foods you eat every day. You'll find high levels of vitamin C in citrus fruits, strawberries, kiwi, guava, peppers, tomatoes, broccoli, and spinach. Teen guys need 75 mg and girls need 65 mg of vitamin C a day.

Thanks for sharing this great information with us Mrs. Hammons!

post_text:
Last chance to sign up for Spring soccer travel league is February 7th!

We will be having a walk-in registration this Thursday at 6:00 pm to 7:30 pm at Carson Park.
If your child was born prior to 2012, they would be a travel player.

The following are age groups that are still needing more to form for travel:
U10 girls - birth years 2010-2011
U12 girls and boys - birth years 2008-2009
U14 girls and boys - birth years 2006-2007

For children born in 2012 and later; they will be in our in-house division and will play all games at Carson Park. Their deadline is February 28th.
If you can't make it to walk-in registration, you can always pick up a registration form at Bank of Commerce and turn it in there. If you have any questions, call Josh Sam at Bank of Commerce.

post_text: Mrs. Brown‚Äôs class made balloon rockets for their space unit this week. They measured the distance the balloons flew in yards, feet, and inches. They discussed why some balloon rockets traveled further than others by using new vocabulary words. Then they had a snack of Capri sun, the packaging has been used in the space station.. and ate dried fruits. This unit began with our Sun, then the Moon, then our planets and ended with space travel. Looks like they enjoyed learning about space!

4th Graders in Mrs. Cochran's class got an early Christmas present when they found out their class would be getting WeDo 2.0 Robotics Kits in January! The kits were purchased from LEGO Education using a grant funded through a Donors Choose project written by Mrs. Cochran.

The students have been working with KuBo Robots this semester. They are learning to write code using coding tiles. Check out the video of Rebekah Baker talking about the code she wrote to tell her robot to travel from the flagpole to the bus stop!

shared_text:
Oklahoma State Department of Education
December 13, 2019 at 12:55 PM ¬∑

This past Monday, we had the privilege of joining students from 25 classrooms across the state to witness holiday cheer in action! Students decked the halls of the Oklahoma History Center with hand-crafted ornaments and Christmas trees, while Governor Kevin Stitt, First Lady Sarah Stitt and State Supt. Joy Hofmeister visited with the children and snapped a few holiday photos.

Thank you to everyone who made the annual Governor's Christmas Tree Lighting Ceremony a success for these Oklahoma schoolchildren. Watch our video of the event to see when Gov. Stitt flips the lights on this year's Capitol tree!

post_text: Mrs. Fourkiller‚Äôs class had an amazing time at the Oklahoma City Tree Lighting Ceremony! They decorated their own class tree with handmade ornaments that will be displayed in the Oklahoma History Museum for the rest of the holiday season. Then they were able to tour the museum, and get a picture with Santa, State Representative, David Hardin, Governor Stitt and his wife, and Joy Hofmeister. The day ended with the annual lighting of the tree outside the museum. So many great memories were made today!
